🎯 Short Answer First

👉 Cursor pagination does NOT support random page jumping like page 79.

That’s not a bug.
That’s by design.

🧠 Why Offset Can Jump to Page 79

With offset pagination (like with will_paginate):

User.limit(10).offset((79 - 1) * 10)

We can calculate:

OFFSET = 780

Database skips 780 rows and gives next 10.

It works because offset pagination is based on row position math.

🚨 Why Cursor Pagination Cannot Do That

Cursor pagination works like this:

Give me 10 records after id = 54231

It does NOT understand:

page numbers

total pages

row positions

It only understands:

“after this record”

“before this record”

So if user says:

Give me page 79

Backend says:

I don’t know what page 79 means.

Because cursor pagination is sequential.

🎯 So What Happens in Real Systems?

In real-world systems (feeds, APIs, large datasets):

👉 We do not allow random page jumps.

Instead we use:

Next

Previous

Infinite scroll

Examples:

Instagram feed

Twitter feed

LinkedIn feed

GitHub issues

They don’t show “Go to page 79”.

🧠 Deep Explanation (Interview Level)

Offset pagination is:

Positional navigation

Cursor pagination is:

Sequential navigation

Offset = book page number
Cursor = bookmark

If you use a bookmark system, you cannot jump to page 79 unless you flip through pages one by one.

🚀 If Interviewer Pushes Further

They may ask:

But what if business REQUIREMENT says jump to page 79?

Correct answer:

Option 1️⃣

Use offset pagination.

Cursor pagination is not suitable.

Option 2️⃣ (Advanced Hybrid Approach)

You can simulate page 79 by:

Calculating offset internally

Fetching the cursor value at that offset

Then using cursor pagination

Example:

cursor_record = User.order(:id).offset(780).limit(1).pluck(:id).first

Then:

User.where("id > ?", cursor_record).limit(10)

⚠️ But this defeats the performance benefit.

Because you still used OFFSET internally.

So this is rarely used.

🎯 Real Architectural Decision

Use:

| Use Case                      | Use    |
| ----------------------------- | ------ |
| Admin panel with page numbers | Offset |
| Public API                    | Cursor |
| Infinite scroll               | Cursor |
| Large 10M+ table              | Cursor |
| Jump to page 50 needed        | Offset |


🎤 Interview-Ready Answer

You say:

Cursor pagination does not support random page jumps like page 79 because it is based on sequential navigation using a reference value, not row positions. If random access is required, offset pagination is more appropriate. In large-scale systems, cursor pagination is typically used for APIs and infinite scrolling where sequential navigation is sufficient.

